# What is a Class 
- Template that defines behavior of an object
- Contains definitions of 
	- properties (data) 
	- Methods (behavior)
	- Events (reaction to things that occur)
- Blueprint of house is a class 
- defines data and functionality to work on its data
#  Naming  Of Class 
- Name classes as nouns or noun phrases  (Customer, Person, Product)
- Use PascalCasing (Customer not customer) 
- User singular (Customer instead of Customers)  
#  What Should Be a Class
 - Any Physical item you are modeling in the real-world 
	(House, Car Person, Bank Statement)
 - Can be Technical Concept as well 
	(Table in a database, File in a folder)
 -  Each of the items mentioned (Have data, you can perform some operation on them) 
# Contents of a Class 

- Fields - Fields contain data. A Field is a variable that is declare directly at the class level
- Methods - Methods define Functionality
- Properties - Properties Control Access to data
- Access Modifier - Define Access to members (public / private)
- Events
- Constructors - Are used for initialization

```c# 
public class Employee
{
    public int Id { get; set; }
    public string FirstName { get; set; }
    public string LastName { get; set; }
    public string Email { get; set; }
    public string Department { get; set; }
    public decimal Salary { get; set; }
    public DateTime DateOfJoining { get; set; }

    public string FullName => $"{FirstName} {LastName}";

    public Employee(int id, string firstName, string lastName, string email,
                    string department, decimal salary, DateTime dateOfJoining)
    {
        Id = id;
        FirstName = firstName;
        LastName = lastName;
        Email = email;
        Department = department;
        Salary = salary;
        DateOfJoining = dateOfJoining;
    }

    public void GiveRaise(decimal percentage)
    {
        if (percentage <= 0)
            throw new ArgumentException("Percentage must be greater than zero.");

        Salary += Salary * (percentage / 100);
    }
}
```


# What is an Object? 
- an instance of a class 
- Object is the logical entity you program against 
- With each object you 
	Set properties 
	Call methods 
 - Response to and raise events 
- The house build from blueprint is object  

# Differences Class / Object 
  - Class is a blueprint, or a template
  - Object is an instance of the template 
  - You can't live in a blueprint, only in a house!
  - You can't interact with a class, only an object 

# Types in the CTS (Common Types System)
- Class
- Enumeration
- Struct
- Interface
- Delegate
- Record 
# Property
- Properties wrap data and can control its value
- Combination of private field and public method
- Contain get and set accessors
- Can contain logic to check value
- Describes the attributes of an object
- Template Defines the properties
- Object Supplies values
- Each Object Maintains its own data storage

```c#  
public class Employee
{
    public string Name { get; }

    public Employee(string name)
    {
        Name = name;
    }
}
```

#  Method
- Public if part of the public interface
- Can work with private fields to change state of object they belong to
- Method defined by the class
- Can return a value
```c#  
public void IncreaseSalary(decimal amount)
{
	if (amount <= 0)
		throw new ArgumentException("Increase amount must be positive.");

	Salary += amount;
}
```
# Constructor
- Constructor is used to instantiate an object with initial values
	- Numeric to 0
	- Char to’\0’
	- Boolean to false
	- References to null
- A default constructor is created for us Only if we don’t include another constructor!
- .Net runtime calls this method  Automatically
- The Default Constructor is not visible. Not created when any other constructor is created


# Constructor Or Method Overloading
- Method Names can be reused
- The combination of Parameters (number, order, data types) must be unique
- A constructor can be chaining


#  Static
- static data is is data stored on the class, and all objects created based on that class will have access to this data. This data is effectively shared between all objects and they can change it. If one object changes it, it's changed for all other objects using the data. Here we have the Product class again.
- A static method, that is a method that is also defined on the class, can work with static data, and it can be invoked on a class rather than on an object.
- Only accessible though class since it’s created at class-level 
- Add Static  to Classes,  methods or  properties 
- Only a Single instance of the  class or property is  created  for  the  running  Application 
- Access  method  or  property through  the  class Name
#  static vs Instance
- Some classes provide both static and instance members
- Instance members belong to each instance of a class
- static members belong to the class, not a specific instance

# Fields
- Instance Variable
- Typically, private (also the default)
- Hiding the information inside the class > Encapsulation
- must be accessed through methods or properties
- Access Modifiers (private, public, protected, internal)

# The Pillars of OOP
-  Abstraction
- Encapsulation
- Inheritance
- Polymorphism
# The concept of abstraction
- Think about the essential concepts, not the background details
- Create layer of abstraction
- Expose simple handles to interact without knowing about the details
- Focus on what it does, not how it does it
#  Encapsulation
-  All data and functionality on this data is encapsulated inside object
-  Only certain information is exposed
- Data is hidden inside the object
- Use access modifiers
* some data is never exposed and thus only used for only inner workings
- Through Access modifiers, we apply encapsulation


# Inheritance
- Inherit features from other classes
- Create hierarchy • Is-A relation
- Improve reuse of code between parent and child class
- The child class can extend functionality and attribute
- Child class will inherit from all anccestors
- Allow reuse of functionalities of base (parent) class for derived (child) class
- Access to members is controlled using access modifiers
- Inheritance Is Transitive Child class will inherit from all ancestors
- Calling the Base Constructor with Parameters The base constructor needs to get values for its constructor and will execute before the derived class constructor executes . Uses the base keyword, passing in the list of arguments.
# Polymorphism
- Allow methods to execute differently
- virtual and override keywords in C#
- On objects of different types, we can invoke the same methods
- Poly and morph > “many-shaped”
- Allow treating objects of derived class as base class object
- Based on virtual and override keywords
- Override base class method with new implementation
- Parameter lists need to be the same, otherwise overloading
